Forty healthy adults aged 18-40 (20 male, 20 female) will be recruited for in this study. Male and female participants will be matched on age and handedness, and will be free from psychiatric (e.g., schizophrenia, depression), neurological (e.g., epilepsy, seizures) and genetic (e.g., Fragile x syndrome) conditions. Ten of the participants that attend the first testing session (5 male, 5 female) will be asked to return for a second MRI scan following the upgrade of the MRI scanner at SNI to a Siemens 3T Prisma, in order to test the replicability of the results between the original Siemens 3T Trio and the new Prisma. 

Participants will be recruited via targeted email, social media advertisements (Facebook, Twitter, etc.), flyers posted around Swinburne University’s Hawthorn Campus and Deakin University’s Burwood Campus (Appendix A), and the Swinburne University Research Experience Program (REP).

Inclusion Criteria
Male or female;
18-40 years of age;
Fluent in written and spoken English;
Normal or corrected to normal vision with contact lenses;
Normal or above normal hearing;
No intellectual disability (IQ &gt; 70).

Exclusion Criteria
Does not meet criteria for MRI
A regular smoker (&gt; 1 cigarette per day);
Requires glasses and/or hearing aid for normal vision and hearing, respectively
A history of neurological conditions (e.g., epilepsy, seizures) or head injury;
A developmental disorder (e.g., ASD, ADHD) or intellectual disability
A psychiatric condition (e.g., depression, anxiety, schizophrenia);
A current substance use disorder;
A genetic condition (e.g. Fragile X syndrome);
Currently taking any prescription medication (except the contraceptive pill or antibiotics);
Pregnant (female only).

On the day of testing, the following exclusion criteria also apply:
Consumed caffeine in the last 12 hours;
Consumed alcohol in the last 12 hours;
Consumed nicotine in the last 12 hours;
Consumed recreational drugs in the past week;
Taken any additional medications since the beginning of the study (except for allergy medication, the Pill, etc.).

